results.notes: Sarasota, FL – Oak, pine and palm nearby but these specimens were much nearer to the oak. Their scent is indistinct. As for taste, I was surprised initially to find they were not tart or acidic after licking the cuticle and nibbling some flesh (with cuticle attached), but after going back today and peeling a large piece of the cuticle off I was getting the expected acidity. All the bruising reactions were nearly instantaneous, including those to the cuticle staining close to black. After bisecting there were varying levels of pink to purple tones on the cap flesh but I suspect these are due to the insect holes throughout that also were bruised red. The last few pictures are of the two specimens as they are today, having their flesh turn a nice yellow orange color with streaks of red and the bruised tubes gaining an orange appearance. (The few indoor photos were taken with a 6500K light source and the colors came through accurately to my eye)

results.notes:
Several fruitbodies scattered in short grass/moss under old oaks.
The distinguishing features of this species are viscid to glutinous (in wet weather) pallid yellow caps with darker yellow-tan discs (oac898-897 to oac4, oac856-855) , covered on disk with small whitish to grayish to grayish-brown pyramidal to subpyramidal warts, striate (0.15-0.25R) to striate-tuberculate cap margins (in mature specimens), glabrous whitish to very pale yellow, totally exannulate (gill edges covered in fluff even in young/immature basidiomata) stipes, and sublobose to obboviod stipital bulbs devoid of well-defined volval remnants. No odor detected; flesh not tasted. Ellipsoid spores apparently don’t exceed 10 microns (x400, no mounting agent); more exact measurements TBD.
Dimensions of the largest saved fruitbody:
Overall height = 8.6 cm
Cap = 7.5 × 8 cm wide, 6 mm thick above stipe
Gills = up to 7 mm wide max
Stipe = 8 cm long, 1.2 cm wide at the flaring apex, narrowing to 1 cm (1 cm below apex) then gradually broadening to 1.5 cm just above the bulb; bulb = 1.5 cm tall, 2 cm wide

results.notes:
Discovered this odd fungus growing from leaf covered soil, roughly parallel to the ground. At first thought it might be an extremely robust stem of a bolete that had lost its cap somehow but there really was no sign of circular trauma at the top of the “stem” where the cap should have been.
Noticed it when I sat down to collect a Lobster mushroom that I had spotted nearby and thought it could be a russula deformed by parasitic infection. It was quite heavy and robust, sectioning showed it to be a solid mass. The smell was unusual…the only way I can describe it is that it smells like Psilocybe cubensis to my nose, a strong “spicy” smell is how I describe it. Given it’s appearance, I might speculate that whatever it is, it could be a potent aphrodisiac. I would appreciate help with identification.
